posts.raw_content:
I was born in 1962, and my life was driven by a work ethic thanks to supportive and demanding parents.

As a kid, we Boomers mowed lawns in the neighborhood for money and looked forward to snow storms in the off season.  A snow shovel and a driveway meant cash.

When I was 16, I was climbing trees with a chainsaw with a 21" bar - limbing and topping.

When I went to college, I had some financial help from my parents, but I worked two jobs.  At least 60 hours per week over summers in the restaurant industry, and then another 30 hours when back on campus.

I graduated, got a job, a roommate, and a piece of shit car.

We sat in lawn chairs and had dinner on an ironing board, and when we had visitors to our shit-box there was a pile of sweaters near the door, because we didn't waste money on luxuries like heat.

We were frugal and eventually became successful. 

We didn't take vacations, and we actually made our own coffee in the morning.
